bib.title: Light-ion production in the interaction of 96 MeV neutrons with carbon

free_txt: Experiment was performed using
a neutron beam facility at The Svedberg Laboratory
Uppsala
Compiled by S.H.
SD: ERR-S in Subent 51 was corrected.
OS. Updated STATUS in subs. 47-56 and
REACTION in subs. 52-56.
Data corrected for
- for particles stopped in two dE detectors
- electronic collimation for few detectors
- target thickness
- time-of-flight shifts and wrap-around
The charged particles are
detected by the MEDLEY setup. It consists of eight
three-element telescopes mounted inside a 24 cm high
cylindrical evacuated chamber with 90 cm
diameter.Each telescope consists of two fully depleted
dE silicon surface barrier detectors and a CsI(Tl)
crystal. The thickness of the first dE detector was
either 50 or 60 mu-m, thickness of the second dE was
either 400 or 500 mu-m. They are both 23.9 mm in
diameter (nominal). The cylindrical CsI(Tl) crystal,
50 mm long and 40 mm in diameter,  served as
the E detector.
Statistical uncertainty
Experiment was performed using
a neutron beam facility at The Svedberg Laboratory
Uppsala
Two different (cylindrical) disks of graphite are
used as the carbon targets. The target diameters
were 25 mm and 22 mm, with thicknesses of 150 mu-m
and 500 mu-m, respectively. Each target was
suspended in a thin aluminum frame using thin wires.
